	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Jamaica prepares to meet the restructuring challenge</h1>

			
			<h4>
												15 September 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The Jamaican agriculture minister, Roger Clarke, has called on ‘farmers to increase their yields through greater efficiency’, thereby lowering costs and allowing full capacity utilisation. This he maintains is the only way to respond to EU sugar-sector reform. He further urged diversification into ‘by-products such as ethanol, bagasse for cogeneration and to increase rum production’. Meanwhile the Jamaican minister of finance and planning, Dr Omar, said that while ‘there is no open cheque book ... we are committed to ensuring that the Sugar Company of Jamaica not only survives but reaches the efficiency levels to deal with the challenges we face’. Meanwhile, former sugar-estate chairman Roy Barrett has expressed scepticism about the long-term future of certain sections of the Jamaican sugar industry, stating ‘even if they give us another moratorium, eventually the price will go down, so we will just be buying time’. With reference to production costs on the Trelawny estate he said ‘I don’t think that we can bring it to a productivity level that can make it competitive on the world market’. Representatives of cane farmer however highlighted how limited were the agricultural diversification options in the Trelawny area.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Jamaican Information Service</i> (June 28th 2005)</p><p>

<a href="http://news.caribseek.com/Jamaica/article_16181.shtml" target="_self">http://news.caribseek.com/Jamaica/article_16181.shtml</a> <br/> </p><p> Press report ( <i>Jamaican Observer,</i> July 17th 2005) 
<a href="http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/html/20050716T200000-0500_84286_OBS_TRELAWNY_SHOULD_GET_OUT_OF_CANE__SAYS_CUSTOS_.asp" target="_self">http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/html/20050716T200000-0500_84286_OBS_...</a> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> In formulating the trade dimension of its response strategy the EC has implicitly assumed that certain producers will no longer be able to supply the EU market at the lower price and will withdraw, as has already been the case for St Kitts &amp; Nevis. On the basis of certain countries withdrawing, other lower-cost ACP producers would then be able to expand the volume of their exports to the EU, thereby partially off-setting the EU sugar-price reductions. However, as the Jamaican government has made clear, they are not simply willing to allow their sugar industry to collapse and are actively pursuing restructuring so as to enable Jamaican producers to continue to supply the EU sugar market. If this is the case, the question arises: where will the additional market access come from to allow low-cost non-LDC ACP suppliers to expand their duty-free exports to the EU in order to offset EU sugar-price reductions?</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
